🌐 IP Address Classes

⚡ Sabse pehle, IP address = 32 bits ka number (IPv4).

        Dotted Decimal Format: 192.168.1.1 (4 Octets = 8 bits each = total 32 bits).
        
        Har IP address do part me hota hai:

                  Network ID (konsa network ka hissa hai)
                  
                  Host ID (us network me kaunsa device hai).

👉 Classes ka use pehle kiya jata tha IP address ko alag alag size ke network me divide karne ke liye. (Aaj VLSM/CIDR use hota hai, but classes exam/interview ke liye important hai).

🔹 Class A

          Range: 1.0.0.0 to 126.255.255.255
          
          Default Subnet Mask: 255.0.0.0 (/8)
          
          Network Bits: 8, Host Bits: 24
          
          No. of Networks: 128 (2⁷, because 0 & 127 reserved)
          
          Hosts per Network: ~16 million (2²⁴ - 2)
          
          Use: Very large networks (ISPs, Government).
          
          Example: 10.0.0.1

🔹 Class B

          Range: 128.0.0.0 to 191.255.255.255
          
          Default Subnet Mask: 255.255.0.0 (/16)
          
          Network Bits: 16, Host Bits: 16
          
          No. of Networks: ~16,000
          
          Hosts per Network: ~65,000 (2¹⁶ - 2)
          
          Use: Medium-sized organizations.
          
          Example: 172.16.0.1

🔹 Class C

          Range: 192.0.0.0 to 223.255.255.255
          
          Default Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.0 (/24)
          
          Network Bits: 24, Host Bits: 8
          
          No. of Networks: ~2 million
          
          Hosts per Network: 254 (2⁸ - 2)
          
          Use: Small networks (offices, home).
          
          Example: 192.168.1.1

🔹 Class D (Multicast)

          Range: 224.0.0.0 to 239.255.255.255
          
          Use: Multicast groups (one-to-many communication, like IPTV, video conferencing).
          
          Not for normal host assignment.
          
          🔹 Class E (Experimental)
          
          Range: 240.0.0.0 to 255.255.255.255

          Use: Experimental, reserved for future/research (not used in practice).


🔑 Quick Trick to Identify Class
(Shortcut)
👉 Look at first octet (first number) of IP address:

| First Octet Range | Class            | Default Mask  |
| ----------------- | ---------------- | ------------- |
| 1 – 126           | A                | 255.0.0.0     |
| 128 – 191         | B                | 255.255.0.0   |
| 192 – 223         | C                | 255.255.255.0 |
| 224 – 239         | D (Multicast)    | –             |
| 240 – 255         | E (Experimental) | –             |



📝 Real-Life Example

Home Wi-Fi → 192.168.1.1 → Class C

University Network → 172.16.0.0 → Class B

Big ISP backbone → 10.0.0.0 → Class A
